age, Performance, Media Event: the National Commemoration of the Second World War in the Netherlands -- tNo Fun: Mourning the Loss of Tragedy in Contemporary Performance Art -- tNotes on the Editors -- tNotes on Contributors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  a‘Panic’ and ‘mourning’ are two pivotal constructs that often emerge and interplay under circumstances of conflict, violence, crisis, and catastrophe, both natural and man-made. Whereas panic tends to crop up during the experience of violent events, mourning, on the other hand, relates to the aftermath of a brutal disruption and to the way humans try to make sense of it retrospectively. Conversely, violent events can leave a thread of panic in their aftermath, while mourning can be unsettled, interrupted or even refuelled by another catastrophic incident. From an international and inter-disciplinary outlook, this volume wishes to address questions at the interface of panic and mourning and their impact on practices in literature, media, and the arts. Since violent events take place within cultures that will draw from their traditions, memories and systems of beliefs in order to process them, the authors of this book aim precisely at discussing the effects of calamity upon the cultural structure and the way literary, artistic and media practices not only reproduce individual and collective anxieties but also generate knowledge and reshape the cultural formation within which they emerge.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aCrisis in literature. 0aLiteraturexHistory and criticismxTheory, etc. 0aLoss (Psychology) in literaturexElectronic books. 0aMourning customs in literature. 0aPsychic trauma in literature. 4aKulturwissenschaft. 4aPanik. 4aTrauer. 4aTrauma. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aCulture.  aMourning.  aPanic.  aTrauma.1 aAgostinho, Daniela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAgostinho, Daniela, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aAntz, Elisa, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBanki, Luisa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrisley, Lucy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aColla, Elisabetta, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDuindam, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFerreira, Cátia, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGanito, Tânia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGonçalves, Diana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMiljković, Milan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPehkoranta, Anna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRibeiro, António Sousa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSurmann, Frauke, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTorres, Eduardo Cintra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTygstrup, Frederik, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWang, Ban, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWeissberg, Liliane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDGBA Backlist Complete English Language 2000-2014 PART1z978311023857008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDGBA Backlist Literary and Cultural Studies 2000-2014 (EN)z978311023846408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDGBA Literary and Cultural Studies 2000 - 2014z9783110637854oZDB-23-GLC08iTitle i